title: Playing field for Dominion
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: This is a playingfield for the card game "Dominion". It helps to store and sort the decks of cards and reduces the space they need on the table. There are enough cases (24) to play the game with all expansions. This thing was created in the fab lab at RWTH Aachen University: http://hci.rwth-aachen.de/fablab

The playingfield has to be cut out of a 3mm board with a laser cutter. I used a MDF board but you can also use other materials.   
Cut the blue lines first, then the black lines.  
The arrangement of the parts is optimized for two boards. The size of the first one has to be at least 600mm x 300mm, the second one at least 400mm x 200mm.  
Use the building instructions to assemble the parts.  
Do not laser cut PVC, Vinyl, Neoprene!

This is a design for an electric ducted fan powered football. In addition to the printed parts, this football requires the following:
-a 70mm fan (left handed version)
-an edf motor no larger than 28mm od
-a shaft adapter to fit the fan onto the motor
-a 40- 80 amp speed controller
-lipo batteries. I used 2 1000 mah 3s batteries wired in series and placed on opposite sides of one another to balance the weight
-a pwm control signal. I am using a servo tester but a microcontroller/accelerometer combo would be better for detecting throws and catches.
-a method of attaching the components inside of the shell. I packed them in with bubble wrap and tape. total weight: 25 oz or less A WORD OF CAUTION: THIS THING MIGHT BE DANGEROUS AND IS NOT A TOY! Build and use at your own risk. This device consumes a large amount of power and has components that spin at extremely high speeds. Safety glasses and protective gear are advised. Crash survivability has not yet been tested but I predict that it is extremely low. I would also avoid catching this with anything other than a fishing net at the end of a 10 foot pole. Here is a bench test video of the edf unit:
http://youtu.be/sk74hzTnlg4

Glue the football tip onto the football inlet using acetone.  
EDF unit fits snugly into football inlet part.  
Attach the football inlet part to the football exhaust part using tape or a better idea.  I used velcro pads which double as grip elements.  
The halves can be bolted together using the internal ribs as well.  Small holes would just need to be drilled in the football exhaust part's exterior shell for access to the bolts.  
Distributing the weight to make it nose heavy will help with stability.

part list
6mm160mm rod x2
M416 screws x2
M316 screws x6
M310 screws x2
M3 nuts x2 Just use the M4 screws to fix the part1 to part2, be careful not fasten to much.
Use M3*16 with nuts to fix part5 to part2.
Put the rod though the hole of the part5, use part3 and part4 to limit the position. Use the screws to fix it.
Stick some tape to fix the gopro!

Rod connector on the cradle is angled from the rough center of mass of the projector unit.

description.text:
The 3D Maze V2 - is based on an article from Scientific American September 1988.
The present design of the maze inclusive the „actuator“ structure is by me.

The object is to move the "actuators" from one corner to the other.
You have to figure out that a possible movement in one dimension can be blocked in the next one.

To build the machine you have to print out each wall (panel). I did this with the inside on the build plate to have a good outside structure. Make sure all „maze corridors“ are smooth. Alternatively you can print all panels, except the top one, at once, and then later glue the top on the box. For this you have to use supports and break those out later. Also you have to polish those openings that were filled by supports.

Presently the puzzle is not too difficult. Maybe in the future I will invest time to make it a bit "more challenging".

Because i am new to 3D printing I will be glad for tips and suggestions.
Also i am saving money for a printer with more possibilities. So if you like please donate something.

Printer:

Da Vinci Mini w

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.3 mm

Infill:

10%

Notes:

I did have to fight warping, so use your own experience to prevent warping of the components during printing. I could not prevent warping completely but using a strong construction lamp to heat up the model seemed to improve the result.
I am glad for any tips on how to prevent warping. (I am new to 3D printing and so far brims did not prevent warping, and rafts damage the surface)

You need to print the actuators 3 times. To assemble the actuators you have to cut one, actuator leg temporarily. Assemble the structure inside the box and glue the cut after assembly.
Make sure all surfaces are as smooth as possible.

You have to print the knob 6 times.

Assembly and hints

Final assembly is a bit tricky. Assemble the actuators and then glue the panels together one by one. Insert the actuator structure after you have glued 2 panels together.
In the end glue the knobs on the actuators in such way that a smooth movement is possible (try out before you apply glue).

When you build the box at once (alternative) plus the top panel. Assemble the actuators inside the box and then glue the top panel.

I sprayed the box with clear polyurethane lacker.

Overall, the smoother the parts the better it moves. At this moment the movement is a bit "sticky".

I am glad for tips on what glue to use. I used CA but then the bond is "for ever". It is impossible to disassemble without breaking it.

description.text:
The Bullzeye Clock is a penny weight driven mechanical gear clock. It is so named because the face looks like a target and the pendulum is reminiscent of an arrow. It should run for about 8-12 hours depending on your string length.

Penny_weights.stl is from the MakerBot Clock http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:18214

Aside from the 3D printed parts you will need:
4 feet of nylon string
$2.50 in pennies
1/64 stainless steel rods (~2mm)
3.5 feet 3/16 wooden dowel (~5mm)

The pinions are superglued to their corresponding gear numbers but the spacers are not glued. gear1top is glued to gear1bottom and the nylon string is wrapped 1.5 times around the drum with the counterweight on the left and four penny weights on the right. Make sure gear1 is tight with the rod and rotates it while the other large gears are loose and rotate around their rods freely. For the hand gears only gear10 is tight and turns with the shaft while the other gears are loose. You may want to use some powdered graphite on the rods to keep things turning smoothly.

Please study the photos and TinkerCAD screenshots for assembly.

To adjust the beat of the the clock just move the pendulum bob higher on the rod to speed it up and lower to slow it down.

description.text: I wanted to strengthen my ABS prints, so decided to make an acrylic case.

I attached the roof lifters with foam mounting tape. The sides and lid are mounted with velcro. The door is fuzzy-on-fuzzy velcro with 3 short pieces of hook-side velcro strategically placed so it stays shut when I close it. The lid piece is plywood from a cannibalized desk, and I'm powering the SD3 with an old computer psu. The hinges are glued onto the door and side acrylic sheets with a 2-part epoxy. Make sure to glue with hinge pins (long thin nails) in place. I wrap a bit of microfiber cloth around the filament and stuff it into the filament cleaner, which pops into a hole I drilled in the back plate, so dust is wiped off the filament before it goes into the extruder. title: Reinforced Y Motor Mount (3 points and extended rod connection) for Prusa i3 MK2

description.text:
The original Y motor mount of the Original Prusa i3 MK2 is probably perfectly sufficient but it does look and feel a bit flimsy. This version has three holes for mounting the motor. I extended the holes mating with the rods hoping this will improve the rigidity of the Y motor mount.

2016-11-30:
I added V08 which has tighter tolerances (8.18 mm) on the holes for the rods. This dimension is equivalent to the original part. This version also has a little nudge on the bottom to get your tweezers under to help removing the part from the bed.

Printer:

Original Prusa i3 MK2

50% Triangular

Printed in bq PLA Pure White for prototyping. Final print (black) was printed with Formfutura ApolloX (ASA). Since the Y motor mount is pretty close to the heated bed I would not recommend printing this in PLA for production use.

Print with at least five walls. More is better.

You will need a M4 bolt and nut for the hing parts and M3 bolt and nut for mounting the clamps together to the hinge bracket.

The boxes over the display and controls spaces use the standard mounting holes which I enlarged a bit to 4.2 mm. I didn't use screws yet to mount them, it still stays in place without any screw. The controls box-cover holds a set of allen keys and three SD cards. The display box-cover holds other tools as well as an extra box for larger tools.

title: GoPro to SJ4000 color filter converter

description.text:
This is a converter from GoPro size colour filters to SJ4000 camera size filters.

I bought on Aliexpress diving lenses that where described as GoPro/SJ4000 compatible. When it arrived... well they where only GoPro compatible.

The most logical way out, was to create a converter - but this would make filter so far from camera lenses, that it frame would be visible on recording.

Luckily, this filters can be easily dismantled in three pieces

  • base, that is attached on GoPro underwater lens cover
  • top part, that is keeping filter in place
  • and the plastic, colour filter

I've prepared replacement for first part - base - that is SJ4000 camera compatible (mine is plain, old SJ4000 - no wifi etc), and you can (without any modification) use filter and top cover from original part.

That's it :)

title: XYZ Printing daVinci Jr 1.0 + Cura 2.3.1 + ThreeDub

description.text:
How to use Cura 2.3.1 with your daVinci Jr
(This is a Mac tutorial. I haven't done this on Windows but should be similar I'd guess.)

Step 1 - Get Cura Running

  1. Download and install Cura 2.3.1
  2. Download davinci_jr_platform.stl and davinci_jr.def.json
  3. Open Cura once and Quit otherwise Mac will complain about corrupted app
  4. Copy davinci_jr_platform.stl into /Applications/Cura.app/Contents/Resources/resources/meshes/
  5. Copy davinci_jr.def.json into /Applications/Cura.app/Contents/Resources/resources/definitions/
  6. Open Cura and add Jr as your printer.

Step 2 - Get Printing

Cura produces regular plain gcode but Jr needs it's proprietary 3w files.
(3w is encrypted gcode with some modifications.)
There comes ThreeDub in play.

  1. Download ThreeDub from https://gitlab.com/anthem/py-threedub/tree/master (Thanks to @Anthem for the ThreeDub development)
  2. Install HomeBrew on your Mac - http://brew.sh/
  3. brew install python
  4. pip install --upgrade pip
  5. pip install pycrypto
  6. pip install pyserial
  7. python setup.py install (from downloaded threedub directory)

Done.

Now when you create .gcode with Cura you just need to convert it to .3w file so Jr can work with it.
Simply run command threedub filename.gcode and it will spit out filename.3w file.

Copy it to SD card and enjoy. I'll presume it works via XYZWare's USB printing - never tried.

Known issues/weird behaviour.

  1. Prints are always facing back to front. But prints are fine. If you select Z seam to be at the back - it will be at the back on the print. Seems to be some firmware weirdness.
  2. When printing small objects Z seam can be "blobby". It's perfectly fine with small details on larger objects but some weirdness going on with small objects like calibration cube.
    Never figured it out why, couldn't be bothered hence this affected my print quality in 2% of the cases max. I don't have Jr stock board anymore so never tested this but on new Cura they have Acceleration and Jerk settings - these might help.
  3. No time ETA on LCD. It shows 1m left pretty much all the time. Also reported time in Cura quite differs from real Jr printing time.

Why should you want to mess about with this and what are the benefits?!

  1. You have bigger control of print settings etc.
  2. You can print faster than 30mm/s (Jr Fast mode)
  3. You can set manual temperature for your filament (extremely useful if you are using 3rd party filaments with hacked NFC tags)
    • loads of other little features...

I stopped the print, and saw a pool of hardened plastic on my bed.  There is a huge abrasion across the entirety of the metal frame my motor rests on.  Thankfully, it seems my printer still works, but I'll be honest, I was pretty freaked out.  I've still yet to test whether it can print a full model.  Why do you think this happened?

description.text: This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/0tfBEurIWoT

I did not see any planters that I liked so I made my own using egon's Torqued Vase http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:312670

Print without infill and top. I used 5 layers on the bottom and sides to make it sturdier. I tried with spiral and it came out way too thin but feel free to play with the settings.

Once both parts are printed I drilled some drain holes (they don't need to be perfect, as you can tell by my pictures) in the bottom of the planter and then glued both pieces together with some extra filament in between them to allow water to run out. If someone wants to take the time to redesign this with holes and spacers already in the design feel free but a drill and some super glue was good enough for me. I also added to gravel to the bottom to allow the water to drain better.

description.text:
Just a line of text in a rectangular mold. There's some simple drafting to make the bar come out easier, and option to smooth the text a bit... if you want smoothing you may want to download and run the .scad yourself, or, use Customizer and only set to the non-fast option just before making the thing file, even though the preview times out apparently the final make does not. Also on "slow mode" is a texture to make removal from the build plate easier.

So far, we have only tried hot process gel soap in these molds - cool at room temp for one hour and the soap removes easily with a little spatula (same tool I use for 3D print removal from the build plate, actually).

Printer:

FlashForge Dreamer

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.14

Infill:

10%

Notes:

I printed in ABS, set first layer to 0.30, otherwise normal-ish, 3 perimeters, 3 bottom layers, 4 top layers. Extra top layers and perimeters (maybe 5 and 5) would probably have been a good idea, during the first soap pour we got some bubbling indicating leakage to the interior of the block.

You can add a raft if you want, no great loss if it doesn't remove easily - the printed part isn't the finished product.

Hot acetone vapor bath to smooth ABS

If you want to get rid of the print artifact texture, a hot acetone vapor bath for ~5 minutes does the trick. Careful not to overdo the acetone, it will eventually open up pathways through the part skin into the interior.

Also: acetone vapor (hot or otherwise) is flammable/explosive - read up on Google about what you are getting into before attempting a hot acetone vapor bath. I do mine outside of the house, and I bring hot water from the inside stove to do the heating, so no exposed flames are in the area of the acetone.

Open SCAD

description.text:
It probably won't get easier than this: in terms of material usage, building effort and general usability this bedside phone holder shows a rather radical design. Made from a small piece of plywood it super easy to make on a small cnc-machine. It can be taken apart without tools, can be stored flat and even works for small tablet computers.

This build was done on a desktop cnc-machine by Stepcraft from 6 mm beech plywood using a spiral-toothed 1.2 mm flute.

Visit https://www.zenziwerken.de/en/ for more interesting designs.

Keep in mind that the stl-file is for viewing purpose only. It will not work if you print this on a fdm-printer.

Consider a small donation (e.g. 1$) if you like this design. Any amount will help me keeping up with my work.
Set your CAM to cutout the two rectangles, then create a pocket around 1.5 mm mm deep and proceed to create parts (cutting on the outside) from the inner to the outer part.
After drawing in Solid Edge 2D, I build a 3d model ... ... from which I did a rendering.

        EMBASE DE BATEAU

Bateaux télecommandés peu onéreux, créés par récupération et créations numériques.
Projet de:
Alain Ducros et Thibault Ayache
Objectif principal :

  • Création de deux embases de bateaux principalement constituées de polystyrène et découpées avec la MiniCut2D.
  • Continuité d'un projet qui consiste à créer un bateau télécommandé par récupération d'un jouet et de pièces imprimées en 3D.

Bateau simple qui ce compose :

  • D'une voiture télécommandée à récupérer où a acheter en vide grenier, et de deux hélices.

  • D'une embase flottante en polystyrène découpée à la Minicut2D et éventuellement pour certaines pièces en bois à la découpe laser.

  • De quelques pièces imprimées en 3D.

Particularité de l'embase A:
Les trois niveaux sont collés à la colle à bois, le niveau inférieur doit avoir une épaisseur de 6 mm a découper à la minicut2D, ici la couche du milieu est doublée, une en bois (découpe laser) et une en polystyrene (MiniCut 2D).

Particularité de l'embase B:
L'embase est au minimum constituée de deux pièces assemblées par un système "queue d’aronde"plus colle à bois, ceci permet de réaliser une embase sans être limité par la zone de travail maximum de la MiniCut2D.

Il est possible de coller plusieurs embases les unes sur les autres et de les alténer pour renforcer l'assemblage. Ici l'embase se compose de trois niveaux :
Une lamelle inférieur "la quille"
Le niveau milieu de 20 mm (fixation des inserts)
le niveau supérieur de 6mm. ( le tenon du niveau supérieur est collé sur la rainures du niveau milieu)

Remarque: une voiture télécommandée de type jouet enfant se compose d'une partie centrale avec l'emplacement des accumulateurs et la carte électronique de contrôle. Il suffit de couper le plastique pour récupérer ce sous ensemble qui est branché au moteur de direction et au moteur de propulsion.
